To the ignoramus, the quote may sound like Maximiano Allegro is relying on chance to decide his starters, but one must ALWAYS read the subtext when it comes to interpreting the Riddler.
>But anon, which coin shows a dog on one side and a cat on the other? Surely he just made it up!
"No!"
The explanation lies in a San Marinese 100 Lire coin from the Seventies, showing the two animals cuddling together ON THE SAME SIDE! This means that Allegro rejects, in fact, a deterministic view of life, and fully embraces the notion of free will in a Dostoyevskyan way [Malo, A. (2017). Nihilism and freedom in the Legend of the Grand Inquisitor. Church, Communication and Culture, 2(3), 259-271.]. It doesn't matter what the coin says, Allegro will always make a rational, yet human, decision, fully willing to bear the eventual consequences of his mistakes.
As an addendum, we state that the choice of a San Marinese coin is not casual: it's in the small city-state that Allegro had his first meeting with Ambra Angiolini, with whom he shared an intense but troubled relationship: in July 1975, the two met in the Antica Trattoria e Locanda Jole, where they were both invited for dinner by a common acquaintance.
The mention of the 1975-minted coin is therefore fully intended, meant perhaps as an inside joke shared with his former sweetheart-a small reverie of the warm Romagna summer nights when they partook in the flames of their budding romance, or maybe as a small playful dig at Rugani and Gatti's homosexual relationship.
To conclude, the authors recommend a holistic approach to Maximiano Allegro's words, which require an in-depth study of his life events and of the cultural zeitgeist that shaped his early life. Only then will one be able to fully appreciate his profoundly Tuscanian wit and the subtleties of his speech, which also translates into his very idea of CALCIO.

as a gringo who has been to Colombia several times now, let me give you my expert opinion. I think there are 2 big reasons

>1) cultural
Colombian culture naturally has a “joie de vivre” about it, but along with that comes a sort of nonchalance. Feeling good and making people happy is valued much higher than hard work. Another thing about their culture: they fucking LOVE Colombia and don’t want to be anywhere else. I think this affects their players playing abroad. Colombia is still a very corrupt country although it’s improved so much in the past 20 years (and hopefully continues despite electing CIA asset commie). Their infrastructure is absolute shit, you can barely drive from Medellin to Bogota. You go through 100 toll booths and the roads still look like absolute shit. Anyways I know nothing about Colombia’s soccer infrastructure (besides Pablo propping up Nacional with laundered money for a few years) but I imagine it’s not great. It's worth reading up on news stories written at the time of the USFL's demise since they aren't tainted by anti-Trump babble that infested American media over the past 6 years.

The USFL was created following what's called the "Dixon Plan", which explained a pro football league to rival the NFL can work and actually be profitable so long as teams don't spend more than $6mil a season and expand very carefully.

Because this was the 1980's and everyone was doing cocaine, a lot of the owners weren't vetted at all, ignored the plan, and began blowing mammoth amounts of money they didn't have. Literally all of the teams except Trump's ran out of money. Good example would be LA's $43mil contract with Steve Young.

The league was dead. Trump suggested suing the NFL for violating anti-trust laws (because he was right, the league was a monopoly), and using the money from the lawsuit victory as a "do-over", kicking out shitty owners and basically restarting the league. It was a low percentage play, but the league's only option.

They WON the lawsuit. People forget that. But the court ruled the financial issues were the result of the individual USFL owners being retards (see above re: blowing money they didn't have) and NOT the NFL's monopoly, so they only awarded them a customary damage amount of $3.67 as opposed to millions

It's a really interesting and nuanced period in pro sports that has been completely re-written by sois with TDS. Trump didn't kill the USFL. 80's excess killed the USFL.

>>128305570
I played in JBO (junior baseball organization). It starts at 3rd grade and uses essentially high school rules. Full stealing bases etc. Players are grouped by age and change age groups every 2 years. 3rd/4th grade, 5th/6th grade etc.

They also have a unique "evaluation" system where all players before the season attend an evaluation and they are judged on batting, fielding and throwing. They are then placed in different skill level groups within their age group. National, American and Federal. Nation is the more recreational level, American is kids who've genuinely trained and Federal is the best 12 kids out of all of them. Federal level requires a very high level of dedication from the child and his family as they will be attending many games and tournaments. There are no all-star teams. All teams stay together for the post-season.

Additionally, the fields grow in size as the players age through the divisions until they reach high school size. This means pitching doesn't dominate as the kids get older but they don't have to move any farther back.

It’s really not, College football is generational. For most college football fans their team isn't just their dad's team or their granddad’s team. It's their great/great-great granddad’s team. Until really the 60's and the AFL-NFL merger, Baseball was king and College football drew more interest than the NFL. The first national brands in American sports were baseball teams NY Yankees, Brooklyn Dodgers, Boston Redsox, Chicago Cubs, etc. The second set of national brands weren’t in the NFL. The second set of national brands were College Football teams. The early growth really starts with the Ivy League in the Northeast. The giant breakthrough is in the 1920’s with Rockne's Notre Dame figuring out how to sell itself with sports writers like Grantland Rice covering them. All over the country early powers who are still national brands today begin to emerge in the 1920s and early 1930s. The teams/schools people latched in the 30’s are the schools their descendants follow today. Michigan is one of those Early Super Brands. During the 60's a crazy thing called Televised sports broadcasting begins to take over. People like Tex Schram, Al Davis, Pete Rozelle, and Lamar Hunt all understood the power of TV and how to exploit it. By the 1970's the NFL with the Super Bowl and Monday Night football are the Kings of Sports and Baseball and College football the old leaders never catch back up. College Football in particular was kneecapped by the original broadcast rules where the NCAA would decide who played on TV each week. That remained in place till 80s. That said, the super college football fanbases created in the 1930’s didn’t just die because of the NFL. The multigenerational college fans stuck around, and will continue to stick around in spite of how fucked up it is now.

Knute Rockne was a legendary football coach at Notre Dame from 1918 to 1930. During his tenure, he led the Fighting Irish to five national championships. He is considered one of the greatest coaches in the history of college football and his influence on the modern game is still felt today.

One of Rockne's biggest contributions to the sport was his emphasis on strategy and tactics. He was a master of the T formation, which at the time was a revolutionary new formation that relied on deception and misdirection to confuse the defense. This formation, along with Rockne's innovative plays, helped Notre Dame become one of the dominant teams of the era and set the standard for how the game would be played in the future.

In addition to his tactical acumen, Rockne was also a master motivator. He was able to inspire his players to perform at their best and instilled in them a sense of pride and confidence. He was also a pioneer in the use of film and scouting reports to analyze opponents and prepare his team for games.

Rockne's success on the field also helped to raise the profile of college football as a whole. He turned Notre Dame into a national powerhouse and helped to create a broader fan base for the sport. His teams were known for their thrilling and exciting style of play, which helped to attract more fans and media attention.

Rockne's influence on modern college football can also be seen in the way coaches approach the game today. Many coaches, including Nick Saban and Urban Meyer, have cited Rockne as an inspiration and have incorporated elements of his coaching style into their own programs.

Knute Rockne's impact on modern college football is undeniable. His emphasis on strategy and tactics, his ability to motivate his players, and his role in raising the profile of college football are all hallmarks of his legacy. Today, his name is still synonymous with the greatest coaches in the history of the sport, and his influence is still felt on the field.
